It was himself, who three years ago criticized Bush’s idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering for civil war, and that criticized him as “an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful, so that nothing is talked about Iraq in the news today.
Bush’s reputation did not improve, yet objectively left his successor a much more favorable initial situation than he could expect.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama expects the miracle to be repeated.
The field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan General Operation Stanley McCristal, who even despite traditional subordinated relationships, submitted to the undecided rifle at the White House to a tough criticism.
He asked 40,000 men to be able to improve the situation.
The president emptied for three months, but he didn’t think anything better, so he at least deceived the general over 10,000 military.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic thing of Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his goal, to start withdrawing Afghan troops in 18 months and finish this procedure in three years.
Many doubt that the increase will be the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite fratricised wars in recent years, Iraq’s society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: it is not possible to trust anyone and no agreements are fulfilled.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces if they are used to change the boss every day according to their needs.
The political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a people of Potemkin, and after him the patriarchal tribal relationships will remain.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated due to confusing relationships, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is "capable of action", a minimum objective of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama’s strategy is shocked by his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to get worse and is now about to explode.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing about reality, may believe that the military sent to war to "soon return home," will do some miracle here.
From the political point of view, fixing the date of the withdrawal of the troops is purely irresponsible, as the Taliban will consider it an indirect statement of the U.S. defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans are increasingly less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians don’t know, and they don’t want to explain to their voters, what relationship has the security of Germany or Italy with the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and increased sanctions do not have any effect on Iranians, the U.S. will have to make a difficult decision: trying to solve the problem with military force or not.
