A Czech discovery: an effective substance even in HIV viruses
Team of Czech and German scientists tests new compounds capable of moderating the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this enhanced substance is that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, as some medicines already accessible.
AIDS disease cannot be cured until now.
However, patients’ life may be significantly extended thanks to a mixture of medications that prevent HIV virus replication in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, the drugs no longer work.
The work of experts from three Institutes of the Czech Academy of Sciences, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They demonstrated that substances called metallocarbone have effect on albumin, responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metalocarbones are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way than all the medicines used today, and therefore they can solve the resistance problem.
In their work, scientists find new, ‘better’ compounds, prepared by knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the virus albumin.
Metalocarbons have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyedre cages composed of the boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are joined by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A traitor and resistant virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease, the fractionation of the HIV virus does not occur and no mature and infectious body of the virus would be created.
If we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient’s body, the scientists explain in a press news published by the Institute of Organic and Biochemistry at the Czech Republic Academy of Sciences.
In an article published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds, in which two pairs of cages (see table) are joined by a short organic series, which remains systematically modified.
