As it happened with ABS brake anti-blocking and will pass with ESP stability control, emergency brake aid systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all new-enrolling light commercial vehicles and cars, while for the rest a period of deficiency is set until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians, although by their way of working it can also help avoid many collisions in reach.
The emergency brake assistant is to increase pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the driver’s footstep.
But he doesn’t always keep that pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by the Bosch car component manufacturer, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident had not reached the brake stepping before the collision and half of them did not take advantage of all the strength.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, instead, requires the maximum braking system, reducing the distance the car employs to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with these types of elements, up to 1,100 mortal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided a year.
The reduction will be even greater – it is estimated that one in four sickness with people damage would be avoided – when so-called intelligent emergency braking systems are popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or a camera) detects the obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps you increase pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In the event that it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device exercises the maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
